\fs36 \cf2 Executive Summary: Strategic Technical Evolution within the BIA Office\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The Central Provident Fund Board (CPFB) stands as a foundational institution in Singapore\'92s social infrastructure, managing the life-cycle security\'97retirement, healthcare, and housing\'97of over four million members. Within this mission-critical environment, the Business Incubator & Accelerator (BIA) Office serves as the spearhead for digital modernization. The Frontier Products Team, a core unit within the BIA, is tasked with the development of cloud-native software products intended to optimize the operational efficiency of the Board and the Whole-of-Government (WOG) ecosystem. During the January to May 2026 internship tenure, the technical mandate focused on three primary pillars: the engineering of AppCentral (a "Vercel-like" deployment platform), the optimization of DraftCentral (a document workflow automation tool), and the exploration of AgentCentral (an autonomous agent orchestration framework).\
This repository serves as a comprehensive record of technical contributions, architectural decisions, and public service impact. It articulates the transition of experimental prototypes into production-grade systems, emphasizing the shift toward agentic AI workflows and the rigorous application of DevSecOps principles within the Singapore Government Tech Stack (SGTS). The analysis reflects the convergence of individual engineering excellence with the national Smart Nation 2.0 vision, specifically addressing the pillars of Trust, Growth, and Community through robust, secure, and scalable software delivery.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Core Technical Contributions: Engineering the Next Generation of Government Platforms\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 AppCentral: Transitioning to an API-First Infrastructure Paradigm\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 AppCentral was conceptualized to function as "Vercel for CPF," providing an intuitive, high-velocity deployment environment for government developers. The primary engineering challenge lay in moving away from legacy database-centric tracking of project states toward a more resilient, API-first architecture. By integrating directly with the Azure DevOps (AzDO) API, the platform achieved real-time synchronization with the underlying repository host, ensuring that the dashboard remained a true reflection of the infrastructure state.\
The implementation of the MVP Dashboard involved a significant refactoring of the frontend architecture. Leveraging Node.js, Next.js, and TypeScript, the codebase was restructured to centralize project logic within \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 src/features/project\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 , while legacy "Teams" and "Approval" routes were deprecated to streamline the user journey. This shift was not merely aesthetic; it involved a deep migration to dynamic routing, which allowed for more flexible state management and improved the system's ability to handle a rapidly growing number of projects.\

